    "Training Strategy": "Loss function: L = λ_PDE·L_PDE + λ_BC·L_BC + λ_data·L_data, where L_PDE = (1/N_PDE) Σ|∇²û + k²û − f|², L_BC enforces boundary values, and L_data (if any measurement data exists) fits observations. Key strategies: (1) Curriculum learning on wavenumber—train at low k first, then incrementally increase k to the target value, transferring weights at each stage. (2) Multi-scale collocation: density of collocation points must satisfy ~10–20 points per wavelength in each direction; for kL large this requires O((kL)²) points, so use adaptive refinement near boundaries and source regions. (3) Loss balancing: use gradient-based or learning-rate-based balancing (e.g., GradNorm or NeurIPS-style weight tuning) so PDE and BC losses contribute equally. (4) Causal/progressive training: weight residuals by distance from the source to impose a propagation-direction bias. (5) Optimizer: Adam with learning rate 1e-3 → 1e-4 schedule, possibly switching to L-BFGS for fine-tuning. (6) For phase-amplitude decomposition, add a soft eikonal regularization |∇S|² ≈ k² in smooth regions. (7) Numerical differentiation: use automatic differentiation for ∇²û; at high k, consider complex-step or spectral differentiation on collocation points to reduce numerical noise. (8) Initialize phase network S to the eikonal solution (ray-tracing or distance function) when available.",
