    "Model Choice": "Use a Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN) with divergence-free architectural hard constraints. Represent B via a scalar magnetic potential A_z(x,y,t) and u via a stream function ψ(x,y,t), each parameterized by separate neural networks (or shared trunk with separate heads). Pressure p(x,y,t) is a separate network output. This guarantees ∇·B = 0 and ∇·u = 0 exactly by construction, eliminating the most common failure mode. Justification: (1) the PDE system is coupled and nonlinear with Lorentz force J×B coupling back to momentum—PINNs handle strong nonlinear coupling via automatic differentiation; (2) sparse observations are naturally incorporated as data loss terms; (3) the vector potential/stream function formulation removes the need for soft divergence penalties, which are unreliable at high magnetic Reynolds numbers. Network architecture: modified MLP with Fourier feature embeddings for spectral bias mitigation, 4–6 hidden layers, 128–256 units, sin/Swish activations. Separate networks for (A_z, ψ, p) or a multi-output network with physically motivated output heads.",
